<section xml:id="subspace">
	<title>Subspace of a vector space</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>We define subspace of a vector space in this section.</p>
	</introduction>
	<definition xml:id="subspace-of-vs">
		<statement>
			Let <m>V</m> be a vector space over a field <m>F</m>. A (nonempty) subset <m>W</m> of <m>V</m> is said to be a <em>subspace of <m>V</m></em> if <m>W</m> is a vector space over <m>F</m> on its own right with operations of vector addition and scalar multiplication on <m>V</m>.
		</statement>
	</definition>

	<remark>
		<statement>
			A subspace <m>W</m> of <m>V</m> is written as <m>W\leq V</m>, and if it is a <em>proper subspace</em> (i.e., <m>W\leq V</m> and <m>W\neq V</m>) then it is written as <m>W&lt; V</m>. 
		</statement>
	</remark>

	<p>We give following criterion to check whether a given nonempty subset of a vector space is a subspace or not.</p>

	<theorem xml:id="subspace-criterion">
		<statement>
			Let <m>V</m> be a vector space over a field <m>F</m>. A nonempty subset <m>W</m> of <m>V</m> is subspace if and only if <m>W</m> is closed under addition and scalar multiplication or equivalently <me>\text{if }\alpha,\beta\in F \text{ and } v,w\in W\text{ then, }\alpha v+\beta w\in W.</me>
		</statement>
	</theorem>

	<example><title>(Trivial subspace)</title>
		<statement>
			For any vector space <m>V</m> over a field <m>F</m>, <m>V</m> and <m>\{0\}</m> are subspaces.
		</statement>
	</example>
	<example><title>(A subspace of <m>n</m>-dimensional vector space)</title>
		<statement>
			Consider an <m>n</m>-dimensional vector space <m>F^n</m> over a field <m>F</m> (refer to <xref ref="vs-examples"/>). Let <m>e_i=(0,0,\ldots,0,1,0,\ldots,0)</m> where <m>1</m> is at the <m>i</m>-th place and <m>i=1,2,\ldots,n</m>. Consider a subset <me>W=\big\{\alpha_1 e_{i_1}+\alpha_2 e_{i_2}+\cdots\alpha_r e_{i_r}:\alpha_i\in F\text{ and } i_j\in\{1,2,\ldots,n\} \big\}.</me> This is a subspace of <m>F^n</m>.
		</statement>
	</example>

	<example><title>(A subspace of <m>n\times n</m> matrices)</title>
		<statement>
			Consider vector space of matrices <m>M_{n\times n}(F)</m> over a field <m>F</m> (refer to <xref ref="vs-examples"/>). A subset of all diagonal matrices in <m>M_{n\times n}(F)</m>, i.e., <me>D_n(F)=\big\{{\rm diag}(a_1,a_2,\ldots,a_n):a_i\in F\big\}</me> is a subspace of <m>M_{n\times n}(F)</m>.
		</statement>
	</example>

	<example><title>(A subspace of the direct sum of two vector spaces)</title>
		<statement>
			Consider the direct sum <m>V\bigoplus W</m> of vector spaces <m>V,W</m> over a field <m>F</m> (refer to <xref ref="vs-examples"/>). A subset <me>S=\big\{ (v,0):v\in V\big\}</me> is a subspace of <m>V\bigoplus W</m>.
		</statement>
	</example>

	<example xml:id="intersection-of-subspace"><title>(Intersection of subspaces)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>V</m> be a vector space over a field <m>F</m>, and <m>I</m> be an indexing set. Let <m>S_i\leq V</m> (<m>i\in I</m>) be subspaces of <m>V</m>. The set <me>\bigcap_{i\in I}S_i</me> is a subspace of <m>V</m>.
		</statement>
	</example>

	<example><title>(Sum of subspaces)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>V</m> be a vector space over a field <m>F</m> and <m>I</m> be an indexing set. For each <m>i\in I</m>, let <m>S_i\leq V</m> be a subspace. The set <me>\sum_{i\in I}S_i=\bigg\{v_1+v_2+\cdots+v_r:v_j\in\bigcup_{i\in I}S_i \text{ and }r\in\N \bigg\}</me> is a subspace.
		</statement>
	</example>

	<example><title>(Solutions of homogeneous system of linear equations)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>A\in M_{m\times n}(F)</m>. The set <me>\ker(A)=\big\{X\in M_{n\times 1}(F): AX=0 \big\}</me> is a subspace of <m>M_{n\times 1}(F)</m>.
		</statement>
	</example>

	<definition xml:id="subspace-span"><title>(Subspace spanned by a nonempty subset)</title>
		Let <m>S</m> be a nonempty subset of a vector space <m>V</m>. The <em>subspace spanned</em> by <m>S</m> is the intersection of all subspaces containing <m>S</m>. We denote it by <m>\langle S\rangle</m>.
		<p>By <xref ref="intersection-of-subspace"/>, the intersection of subspaces is again a subspace. Note that a subspace spanned by <m>S</m> is the <em>smallest</em> subspace of <m>V</m> containing <m>S</m>.</p>
	</definition>

	<theorem xml:id="span-linear-combination">
		<statement>The subspace spanned by a nonempty subset <m>S</m> of a vector space is the set of all linear combinations of vectors in <m>S</m>.</statement>
	</theorem>

</section>